            <![CDATA[
                    <p><img src="https://bartob03.github.io/SJSUInfo23710/media/posts/4/collected_ks-2.jpg" class="type:primaryImage" alt="The collected short stories of Khushwant Singh" /></p>
                <p><span class="TextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0" lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="auto"><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0">Khushwant Singh was a well-known Indian writer and political commentator</span><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0">.  </span><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0">His stories often took on themes of conflict within Indian society. “<em>The Riot</em>” is one of the stories included in “<em>The Collected Short Stories of Khushwant Singh</em></span><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0">”.</span><span class="NormalTextRun SCXW4723392 BCX0"> </span></span><span class="EOP SCXW4723392 BCX0" data-ccp-props="{&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559685&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:160,&quot;335559740&quot;:259}"> </span></p>
<h3>Origin</h3>
<p>Hadali, Pakistan</p>
<p> <div class="post__iframe"><iframe width="400" height="300" style="border: 0;" src="https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d6745.475588757736!2d72.18802154954219!3d32.292026864969785!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x39213b00fe7c0401%3A0x5aa4522dcf3b9f45!2sHad%C4%81li%2C%20Khushab%2C%20Punjab%2C%20Pakistan!5e0!3m2!1sen!2snl!4v1688797725768!5m2!1sen!2snl" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" loading="lazy" referrerpolicy="no-referrer-when-downgrade"></iframe></div>
<h3>"The Riot" short story</h3>
<p>"<em>The Riot</em>" can be read online from the SJSU library.</p>
<p>Singh, K. (2007). <i>The Riot</i>. New Delhi: Penguin Books Ltd. Retrieved from http://search.proquest.com.libaccess.sjlibrary.org/books/riot/docview/2138590642/se-2</p>
<figure class="post__image"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://bartob03.github.io/SJSUInfo23710/media/posts/4/collected_ks.jpg" alt="The Collected Stories of Khushwant Singh" width="300" height="492" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw" srcset="https://bartob03.github.io/SJSUInfo23710/media/posts/4/responsive/collected_ks-xs.jpg 300w ,https://bartob03.github.io/SJSUInfo23710/media/posts/4/responsive/collected_ks-sm.jpg 480w ,https://bartob03.github.io/SJSUInfo23710/media/posts/4/responsive/collected_ks-md.jpg 768w"><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
<h3>Reflect</h3>
<ul>
<li><span data-contrast="auto">What was the conflict in the story? </span></li>
<li><span data-contrast="auto">What do you think Khushwant Singh was trying to say about the similarities between dogs and people?</span></li>
</ul>
<h3>Explore</h3>
<p>Khushwant Singh. (2007). <i>The collected short stories of Khushwant Singh</i>. Ravi Dayal Publisher.</p>
<p>Mukerji, S. (1917). <em>Indian ghost stories.</em> A.H. Wheeler &amp; Co.</p>
